# Tibial Tuberosity

> The **tibial tuberosity** is the prominent bony elevation on the anterior proximal [[Tibia]], just below the knee joint, where the **patellar tendon** (continuation of the [[Quadriceps Femoris]] via the [[Patella]]) inserts.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Tibia]] — anterior proximal tibia
- [[Patella]] — patellar tendon connects patella to tibial tuberosity
- [[Quadriceps Femoris]] — force transmitted through patella → patellar tendon → tibial tuberosity → knee extension

## 🗂️ Key Facts
| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Location | Anterior proximal tibia; easily palpable below kneecap |
| Insertion | Patellar tendon (continuation of quadriceps mechanism) |
| Apophysis | Growth plate in adolescents (Osgood-Schlatter site) |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Osgood-Schlatter disease** — Apophysitis (overuse) at the tibial tuberosity in adolescent athletes; painful prominence; resolves with skeletal maturity
- **Patellar tendon rupture** — Avulsion or rupture at tibial tuberosity; unable to extend knee; infrapatellar gap
- **Tibial tuberosity osteotomy (TTO)** — Surgical repositioning for patellar maltracking
- **Bump palpation** — Tenderness at the tuberosity in Osgood-Schlatter; prominent ossicle may persist into adulthood

